his foot. The neurovascular assessment is normal and the skin is intact.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn X-ray of his ankle joint is performed. (Image)\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Short leg cast or CAM boot and weight bear as tolerated","Short leg cast or CAM boot and no weight bearing for 6 weeks post-operatively","Above the knee cast and no weight bearing for 6 weeks","Open reduction and internal fixation with weight bearing as tolerated","Open reduction and internal fixation with no weight bearing for 6 weeks post-operatively"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe X-ray shows an isolated lateral malleolus fracture with 1mm displacement and no talar shift. The Weber classification classifies the level of the ankle fracture in relation to the syndesmosis. In this case, this injury is a Weber A ankle fracture \u2013 an infrasyndesmotic fracture located below the syndesmosis. This ankle fracture commonly occurs due to ankle inversion. The management of ankle fractures largely depends on Weber\u2019s classification. Ankle fractures below the syndesmosis i.e. Weber A are generally stable and do not require operative management. A \u003Cstrong\u003Eshort cast with weight bearing as tolerated\u003C/strong\u003E should suffice provided this is an isolated fracture.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EShort leg cast or CAM boot and no weight bearing for 6 weeks post-operatively\u003C/strong\u003E is not necessary for a Weber A fracture, as these are stable and can be managed conservatively with weight bearing as tolerated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAbove the knee cast and no weight bearing for 6 weeks\u003C/strong\u003E is excessive for a stable Weber A fracture, which does not require such restrictive immobilisation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOpen reduction and internal fixation with weight bearing as tolerated\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated for a Weber A fracture, as these fractures are stable and do not require surgical intervention.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOpen reduction and internal fixation with no weight bearing for 6 weeks post-operatively\u003C/strong\u003E is appropriate for unstable fractures, such as Weber C, but not for a stable Weber A fracture.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Infrasyndesmotic ankle fractures can be treated conservatively.","The Weber classification system helps determine the stability and management of ankle fractures."],"references":["Kortekangas T, Haapasalo H, Flinkkil\u00e4 T, Ohtonen P, Nortunen S, Laine HJ, J\u00e4rvinen TL, Pakarinen H. Three week versus six week immobilisation for stable Weber B type ankle fractures: randomised, multicentre, non-inferiority clinical trial. BMJ. 2019 Jan 23;364:k5432. doi: 10.1136/bmj.k5432. Erratum in: BMJ. 2019 Feb 19;364:l457. doi: 10.1136/bmj.l457. PMID: 30674451; PMCID: PMC6342249. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30674451/","Moseley AM, Beckenkamp PR, Haas M, Herbert RD, Lin CW; EXACT Team. Rehabilitation After Immobilization for Ankle Fracture: The EXACT Randomized Clinical Trial. JAMA. 2015 Oct 6;314(13):1376-85. doi: 10.1001/jama.2015.12180. PMID: 26441182. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/26441182/","Pakarinen HJ, Flinkkil TE, Ohtonen PP, Ristiniemi JY. Stability criteria for nonoperative ankle fracture management. Foot Ankle Int. 2011 Feb;32(2):141-7. doi: 10.3113/FAI.2011.0141. PMID: 21288412. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/21288412/","Gaillard F. Weber classification of ankle fractures | Radiology Reference Article | Radiopaedia.org [Internet]. Radiopaedia.org. 2020. Available from: https://radiopaedia.org/articles/weber-classification-of-ankle-fractures"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"68037"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2299"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"1912"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"1912","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/1912"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/cb4d44ca-a7f5-410d-9955-7d7a7211a39e.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/cb4d44ca-a7f5-410d-9955-7d7a7211a39e.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":881,"height":902}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"68037","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/68037"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-31T20:57:11+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-31T20:58:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2299"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82978"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"34","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/34"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb4","name":"Orthopaedics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name